(9) Assess the composition and capacities of the members of the Inventory Committee, and take the necessary course of action, such as delineating the duties and functions of the members of the Inventory Committee, or appointing one personnel from each department/office as a member of the Committee who would lead the conduct of the physical count and preparation of the RPCI per department/office;
(10) Strictly require the department heads to submit the RPCI per type of inventory in their custody/office to the Inventory Committee for consolidation and validation within the period required by Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
Require the Inventory Committee/GSO to:
(11) Observe the procedures laid down in the Manual for the receipt, issuance and utilization of inventories; specifically, (i) stop the practice of using the PR as basis for the direct issuance to or receipt of delivered supplies to the requesting department/office, (ii) require the requesting department/office to accomplish the RIS, (iii) consolidate the RIS, and prepare and submit the SSMI to the MAO for recording or updating of the Inventory balances in the books; and (iv) direct the Inventory Committee/GSO to maintain the stock cards, and periodically reconcile those with the ledger cards maintained by the Accounting Department;
(12) Conduct the semestral physical count of all inventories under their custody, and those that are under the custody of the different departments/offices, and prepare and submit the RPCI to the Audit Team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; Restated in Part II of this report.
(13) Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain the supplies ledger card per commodity/stock as required by the guidelines, and periodically reconcile it with the stock cards and property cards maintained by the GSO for checks and balances; and
(14) Require the GSO and Municipal Accounting Office to reconcile the balances found in the financial statements against the results of the physical count to prevent misstatement of inventory balance.

(15) Immediately secure a copy of the court decision affirming the cash shortage incurred by the then Municipal Treasurer against the LGU local treasury;
(16) Enforce the collection of the determined cash shortage; and
(17) Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the cash shortage to the proper FS account, Due from Officers and Employees, with accompanying disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements, to fairly present the Cash-Local Treasury account prospectively.

(18) Closely coordinate and reconcile with the Municipal Assessor’s Office on the timely submission of the Assessment Roll reflecting the updated General Revision of real properties within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
(19) Update the RPTAR/RPTIC based on the submitted Assessment Roll from the Municipal Assessor’s Office;
(20) Prepare the summary list of RPT and SET receivables based on the updated RPTAR/RPTIC and submit it together with the list of taxpayers and their corresponding amount of taxes to the Office of the Municipal Accountant at year-end or the beginning of the succeeding year to be the basis for setting the receivable;
(21) Carefully review the summary and the detailed reports on the RPT and SET Receivables before their submission to the Office of the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the receivables set up at the beginning of the year reflect the true estimate of receivables for the period; and
(22) Maintain a record of taxpayers with unpaid taxes, and regularly update the report based on the RPTAR/RPTIC. Subsequently, reconcile, at least annually, with the Office of the Municipal Accountant to determine the correct balances of the RPT and SET receivables.
(23) Observe the timeline of submission of the assessment roll as well as ensure that the assessment roll submitted was based on the Quarterly Report of Real Property Assessment of the Municipality for the whole year;
(24) Regularly update and timely furnish the Office of the Municipal Treasurer with the Assessment Roll at the end of the year and other transactions affecting the assessment and recognition of real properties in the Municipality; and
(25) Periodically reconcile records with the Municipal Treasurer at least annually to ensure that records are properly updated and to facilitate the establishment of correct RPT and SET receivables at the beginning of the year.
(26) Request for the updated list of taxpayers and the estimated amount collectible from each taxpayer from the MT office and draft the correcting entry to update the balance of the receivable;
(27) Analyze and review the reports submitted by the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to confirm the correctness of the data and presented in the summary report and reconcile records with the Office of the Municipal Treasurer on the unpaid RPT and SET to establish and substantiate the reported receivables in the book, and make the necessary adjustments; and
(28) Ensure that the recorded RPT and SET receivables accurately reflect the balance of receivables at year- end after careful review and analysis to avoid receivables understatement or overstatement of receivables and misrepresentation of the financial statements as a whole; and
(29) Avoid drawing adjusting entries to offset the negative balance of the receivables account rather review and verify the supporting documents from the set-up to collection to determine the appropriate course of action and properly and accurately reflect the balance of RPT/SET receivable and Deferred RPT/SET receivable in the financial statements.

(33) Reassess the LGU’s current planning flow and documentation procedures and determine points of improvement to ensure that the development projects, including those already appropriated for this year, are “well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready”;
(34) Prospectively ensure that only priority projects are appropriated to optimally utilize the 20 percent DF and deliver the desired benefits to the public;
(35) Present to the Audit Team the overall approved plan for the implementation of the construction of the new RHU Building with target timelines and specific financing of this entire development project;
(36) Also direct the Municipal Accountant and Budget Officer to maintain a detailed schedule of loan amortizations and furnish the same to MPDC to ensure accurate DF appropriations for the payment of loan amortizations; and
(37) Charge school-related expenses to the Special Education Fund (SEF);
(38) Immediately submit documents to establish that CBMS is being implemented by the LGU as a comprehensive program/project. Otherwise, stop charging CBMS-related expenses against the 20 percent DF; and
(39) Also reassess the staffing and available equipment in the Municipal Engineering Office and cause the provision of needed personnel and equipment to carry out the handling and overseeing of projects in its intended schedule; and
(40) Direct the Municipal Engineering Office to adopt the prescribed templates and procedures before issuing LGU’s Inspection Report, Certificate of Completion, and Certificate of Acceptance, and faithfully submit the mandatory quarterly utilization report.

(44) Direct the GAD Focal Point System, together with the lead or implementing offices, to maximize the utilization of GAD funds, and monitor the implementation of GAD PAPs so that no activity is left unimplemented at the end of the year and the intended benefits that could be derived from their implementation could be achieved;
(45) Direct the GAD Focal Point System to assess the current capacities of LGU personnel on gender mainstreaming, and propose trainings on the subject matter, when necessary; and
(46) Issue a directive (i.e., memo or executive order) every January to all LGU departments/offices for the preparation of their annual GPB for the succeeding year, and annual GAD AR for the previous year, which shall be due for submission to the GFP System not later than February of the same year [when the directive was issued], together with the relevant supporting documents, such as project/activity proposal, and duly accomplished HGDG tests on their regular/flagship PPAs.

(50) Communicate in writing the identified bank errors, including the long-standing deposits in transit, to depository banks, and request that the respective account’s balance be corrected or updated;
(51) Draw the necessary adjusting entries to revert to the cash-in-bank balance the amounts of the stale checks.
(52) We also recommended that Management refund the unnecessary dormancy fees of ₱3,300.00.

(61) Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Registry of Donated Relief Goods – DRRM, to reflect the full cost of ending inventory of goods/vaccines received and issued, and record in the books the cost of donated PPE less its total accumulated depreciation if there is any;
(62) Instruct the Property and Supply Unit to inspect the donations to the Municipality and maintain the Property Cards of the same for check and balance with the accounting Unit;
(63) Instruct the RHU to prepare and submit a monthly report to the Accounting Office on the receipt, issuance, and balances of vaccines and other inventories directly received from outside sources; as well as to the Property Custodian in terms of receipt of inventories received to record its receipt; and
(64) Instruct the DRRM to prepare the reports/records expected of them in terms of donations in kind, as prescribed in the Circular.

(67) Restate the reported balances of the accounts affected by prior period errors in the comparative FS, and provide a disclosure thereof in the Notes to FS, in accordance with the provisions of IPSAS 3;
(68) Establish proper inventory cut-off, and coordinate with the MDRRMO, and other offices in custody of inventories, for the prompt and regular submission of distribution lists so that expenses are recorded in the proper period; and
(69) Likewise, we recommended that Management direct the MDRRMO to submit the distribution lists for relief goods to the Accounting Office immediately after its distribution, or at year-end as an established cut-off, so that related asset and expense accounts reflect their corrected balances in the period to which they relate. Restated in Part II of this report.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Exert utmost efforts in conducting a thorough review of Cash in Bank records through confirmation, validation, and verification of the reconciling items which were already identified and reflected in the BRS, and prepare the necessary correcting/adjusting entries to reflect the correct balance of the Cash-in-Bank-Local Currency, Current Account;
Communicate in writing the identified bank errors, including the long-standing deposits in transit, to depository banks, and request that the respective account’s balance be corrected or updated;
Ensure that other supporting documents to the BRS such as original copies of DMs/CMs for the ensuing period/s  be submitted to the auditors to facilitate review and examination thereof; and
Draw the necessary adjusting entries to revert back to the cash in bank balance the amounts of the stale checks.

We recommended that Management require the concerned personnel/department to:
secure and maintain a copy of the Memoranda of Agreement or the implementing guidelines governing the implementation and liquidation of grants received from the national agencies;
monitor the status of projects funded by national agencies and timely coordinate with the source agency to ensure that any grant is settled accordingly;
direct the implementing department in coordination with the accounting and treasury department to liquidate and settle their account, in accordance with the condition of the grant, substantiated with complete reports; and
ensure the return of the unused balance to the source agency to fully liquidate the grants in the books of the LGU or request from the source agency to allow the Municipality to utilize the excess fund for other projects, with written confirmation from the latter.

We recommended that Management:
stop the granting of additional cash advances to Accountable Officers and officials/employees unless the previous ones are fully settled;
require employees/officials still in the service to settle all unliquidated cash advances;
send final demand letters to persons no longer connected with the LGU for their unsettled cash advances;
request write-off of unliquidated balances of deceased accountable officers; and
ensure that the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances is in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002.

We recommended that Management require the concerned personnel/department to:
review and re-assess the plans/projects/activities to determine the necessity and adequacy of implementing the identified projects;
prepare and submit concrete project plans and necessary requirements to commence the projects;
secure and maintain copies of the memorandum of agreements or the implementing guidelines governing the implementation and liquidation of grants received from the national agencies;
monitor and evaluate the implementation of the planned PPAs of the LGU and assist the implementing office during the liquidation procedure; and
determine the exact amount of unused fund for completed projects and return the same to the donor/source agency or request for the latter to allow the Municipality to utilize the excess fund for other projects.

We recommended that Management:
stop the granting of additional cash advances to Accountable Officers and employees unless the previous ones are fully settled;
require that all cash advances be fully liquidated at the end of the year;
issue demand letters for the settlement of the unliquidated cash advances granted to accountable officers and employees not anymore connected with the LGU as provided under COA Circular 2017-010.

We recommend that Management require the Municipal Treasurer/designated Property Custodian to:
prepare a complete physical count of all LGU’s properties and present a consolidated RPCPPE;
maintain property ledger cards for each PPE account, in the prescribed form, to facilitate periodic reconciliation;
reconcile noted discrepancies with the accounting records; and
issue Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) for all properties.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Engineer/Project Engineer and Municipal Accountant to:
review and re-assess the plans/projects/activities to determine the necessity and adequacy of implementing the identified projects;
prepare and submit concrete project plan and necessary requirements to commence the project;
revisit the guidelines on Annex E of RA 9184 on the imposition of liquidated damages or cancellation of contract due to delay in the completion of the project.
determine the exact amount of unused fund for completed projects and return the same to the donor/source agency or request for the latter to allow the Municipality to utilize the excess fund for other projects.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Assessor to:
update the Field Appraisal and Assessment Sheets (FAASs) of those properties which were not updated for a long period of time, even when there exists no transaction;
make sure that the fair market values of the real properties, including the improvements, are properly reflected in the tax declarations and FAASs;
conduct actual inspection of real properties whenever doubt arises as to the sworn statement filed by the declarant as to the true value of their property;
prepare a complete copy of the Assessment Rolls in order to properly account for the real properties located in the Municipality; and
coordinate and follow up with the Provincial Government of Camarines Sur as to the status of enforcement of the General Revision, in order to avoid the lax imposition of the supposedly increase in tax collections.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to:
revisit the status of outstanding checks of the LGU to determine whether they are still in the custody of the cashier or in the hands of the payees;

determine, for those checks already issued, whether they are subject for replacement or not;

effect/record in the books the necessary adjustments, as provided for under Section 59 of the NGAs – Volume I, to guarantee accuracy of the cash balance appearing in the LGU’s financial reports; 

ensure that checks, when not claimed, remain in the custody of the Municipal Treasurer and be detached from the original voucher, to facilitate determination of unclaimed vouchers at year-end; and

file photocopies of the vouchers with the individual check for easy reference

We recommended that Management:

(a.)  refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees unless the previous cash advances are liquidated;

(b.)  demand immediate liquidation of all unsettled cash advances, specifically the substantial amount of prior years’ balances, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular 97-002;

(c.)  intensify the regular monitoring of granting, utilization and settlement of all cash advances; and

(d.)  enforce the implementation of the provision in the withholding of salary for officer and employees and AOs with unliquidated cash advances as provided by the above circulars.
